<!-- Modal para el artículo "Output Caching in .NET 8 — A Pragmatic Guide" -->
<div class="modal fade" id="article1Modal" tabindex="-1" aria-labelledby="article1ModalLabel" aria-hidden="true">
    <div class="modal-dialog modal-dialog-centered modal-lg">
        <div class="modal-content" style="background-color:#2a3440; color:#fff;">
            <div class="modal-header">
                <h5 class="modal-title" id="article1ModalLabel">Output Caching in .NET 8 — A Pragmatic Guide</h5>
                <button type="button" class="btn-close" data-bs-dismiss="modal" aria-label="Close"></button>
            </div>
            <div class="modal-body" style="line-height:1.6;">
                <p>
                    <strong>Output Caching</strong> in ASP.NET Core 8 is a lightweight and powerful way to boost performance by reusing full responses that don’t change frequently.
                    Instead of recalculating a view or API response on every request, .NET 8 can store and serve it directly from cache — dramatically reducing CPU, DB, and I/O usage.
                </p>

                <h6>🧠 When to Use It</h6>
                <p>
                    Output caching shines for endpoints where the response remains the same for multiple users — such as public pages, product listings, or slow reports.
                    You can safely cache those responses for a short or long period and serve them instantly.
                </p>

                <h6>⚙️ How It Works</h6>
                <p>
                    .NET 8 introduces a modern middleware-based implementation that replaces the old <code>[ResponseCache]</code> attribute.
                    You simply register it once in <code>Program.cs</code> and use the <code>[OutputCache]</code> attribute wherever needed.
                </p>

                <pre><code>// Program.cs
var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);
builder.Services.AddOutputCache();

var app = builder.Build();
app.UseOutputCache();

// Controller or Minimal API endpoint
app.MapGet("/products", async (MyDbContext db) =>
{
    return await db.Products.ToListAsync();
})
.WithName("GetProducts")
.CacheOutput(p => p.Expire(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(60))); // Cached for 1 min
</code></pre>

                <h6>🚀 Benefits</h6>
                <ul>
                    <li>🔹 Easy to enable — minimal configuration.</li>
                    <li>🔹 Great performance boost for static or semi-dynamic endpoints.</li>
                    <li>🔹 Compatible with distributed caches (e.g., Redis).</li>
                    <li>🔹 Built directly into the ASP.NET Core middleware pipeline.</li>
                </ul>

                <h6>⚡ Real-World Tip</h6>
                <p>
                    Combine Output Caching with <code>IMemoryCache</code> or <code>IDistributedCache</code> for layered performance.
                    Keep it short-lived (e.g., 30–120 seconds) to ensure the data stays fresh while still reducing load on the DB.
                </p>

                <h6>✅ Conclusion</h6>
                <p>
                    Output Caching in .NET 8 is a simple yet powerful tool for boosting response times without adding infrastructure complexity.
                    In high-traffic apps, it can easily reduce backend load by 50–70% with just a few lines of configuration.
                </p>

                <p class="text-muted"><em>5 min read • Published Nov 10, 2025</em></p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

