            <div class="modal-header">
                <h5 class="modal-title" id="article3ModalLabel">Building Resilient APIs with ASP.NET Core and Polly</h5>
                <button type="button" class="btn-close" data-bs-dismiss="modal" aria-label="Close"></button>
            </div>
            <div class="modal-body" style="line-height:1.6;">
                <p>
                    Modern APIs need to be resilient against network issues, transient errors, and external dependencies.
                    <strong>Polly</strong>, integrated natively with ASP.NET Core, provides a powerful way to achieve this without cluttering your code.
                </p>

                <h6>🧩 What Is Polly?</h6>
                <p>
                    Polly is a fault-handling library that helps you define retry, circuit-breaker, timeout, and fallback policies declaratively.
                </p>

<pre><code>// Example: Register HttpClient with retry policy
builder.Services.AddHttpClient("WeatherClient")
    .AddTransientHttpErrorPolicy(p =&gt;
        p.WaitAndRetryAsync(3, attempt =&gt; TimeSpan.FromSeconds(Math.Pow(2, attempt))));
</code></pre>

                <h6>⚙️ Circuit Breaker Example</h6>
<pre><code>p.CircuitBreakerAsync(
    handledEventsAllowedBeforeBreaking: 5,
    durationOfBreak: TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30)
);</code></pre>

                <h6>✅ Benefits</h6>
                <ul>
                    <li>Improved reliability of API-to-API communication.</li>
                    <li>Reduced risk of cascading failures.</li>
                    <li>Better user experience under transient network issues.</li>
                </ul>

                <h6>🧠 Real-World Use</h6>
                <p>
                    Combine Polly with centralized logging (like Serilog) to monitor retries and circuit events.
                    You’ll quickly identify unstable dependencies before they become outages.
                </p>

                <p class="text-muted"><em>6 min read • Published Sep 15, 2025</em></p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
